The article discusses the continuation of the national emergency declared by the President of the United States with respect to North Korea. The national emergency was initially declared in 2008 due to the threat of weapons-usable fissile material on the Korean Peninsula. Over the years, the scope of the national emergency has been expanded to address various actions and policies of the North Korean government, including nuclear tests, missile launches, human rights abuses, and illicit activities in international markets. The President has signed multiple executive orders to maintain certain restrictions and take additional steps to address the national emergency. The most recent executive order was signed in 2023, extending the national emergency for another year. The article emphasizes that the existence and risk of weapons proliferation and the actions of North Korea still pose an unusual and extraordinary threat to the national security, foreign policy, and economy of the United States.